					<div class="commentheading">On June 03, 2010 at 08:07 PM, Dilbert said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject"></div>
					<div class="commentbody">Bill -<br />
<br />
"organic or not" really doesn't enter the picture in terms of salmonella risk.<br />
<br />
salmonella is endemic by geographic region.  in the USA, the major risk _was_ cracked eggs - where salmonella could enter the egg and breed prolifically.  USDA washing/sanitizing regulations (apply only to large producers.....) have dramatically reduced the external induced infection risk.  <br />
<br />
the other vector is "internal" - an infected hen can lay an un-infected egg on day x and an infected egg on day y.  as best I can gather, nobody can explain why.  the egg may be 'infected' with salmonella from the point it leaves the ovaries.<br />
<br />
the 'organic' label is fine, but it is not of any assurance that an egg is salmonella free.<br />
<br />
oh, I'm in the organic camp, but I live in reality . . . just for info.</div>
