					<div class="commentheading">On July 02, 2012 at 04:16 PM, Aunt ria (guest) said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>Failed mayo in a thunderstorm!</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">I made some mayo with an inversion blender recently (it came out fine) and I tried it again just yesterday, but it failed twice.  I had read that u can't do it during a thunderstorm, but didn't believe it. apparantly due to the electrical charge in the air, you can't emulsify during a storm. I am surprised that no one has mentioned this here.  I wasn't even able to save it the next day.  Did anyone else have the same problem?  <br />
<br />
Also, if you like hellmanns or best foods mayo, you can check out top secret recipes for their version.</div>
					<hr size="1" noshade />
				
					<hr size="1" noshade />
					<div class="commentheading">On July 02, 2012 at 06:37 PM, Diane B. said...</div>
					<div class="commentsubject">Subject: <span>&quot;thunderstorm&quot; and making mayo</span><br /></div>
					<div class="commentbody">Interesting...hadn't heard that.  It does seem to show up here and there online and in some old books, etc, suggesting the cause is either excess humidity or something to do with the "positive and negative charges" at those times.<br />
<br />
Here's an exchange I found here where at least someone gives more of a scientific explanation of why it might be true:<br />
http://www.puritanboard.com/f84/i-proved-you-cant-make-mayo-if-thunderstorm-threatening-31528<br />
<br />
[color=darkblue:42e468b80d]If the air is somewhat more highly ionized than normal, if there are reactions going on in the mayo (proto-mayo?) that involve ion exchange, you certainly can have an impact on the process...<br />
Todd K. Pedlar<br />
<br />
I agree. Protein emulsion is dependent on the negative charge of certain amide groups that are chemically reduced. A heavily charge atmosphere can really mess it up.<br />
I used to run into a similar problem in experiments with protein on colloids (basically, I was analyzing what happened to manure in soil, if you really want to know). The emulsions sometimes wouldn't form if there was a big thunderstorm out.<br />
R. Victor Bottomly [/color:42e468b80d]</div>
